In TypeScript, you can use type annotations and type assertions to narrow down the type of a value to a more specific type than what the type system infers. Here's how you can tell TypeScript that "I know that in theory this value may have these multiple types, but in practice I know it will only have this one":

1. Type Annotations: You can explicitly annotate the type of a variable or function parameter to help TypeScript understand its intended type. For example:

```typescript
function getValue(): string | number {
  // ...
}

const myValue = getValue();

// TypeScript infers myValue could be string or number
// You can annotate the type to help TypeScript understand your intention
const myValueAsString: string = getValue();
```

2. Type Assertions: You can use type assertions to explicitly tell TypeScript that a value has a specific type, even if the type system infers a different type. This can be useful when you know that a value has a specific type, but TypeScript is not able to infer it. For example:

```typescript
const myValue = document.getElementById("my-element");

// TypeScript infers myValue could be HTMLElement | null
// You can use a type assertion to tell TypeScript that myValue is actually an HTMLInputElement
const inputElement = myValue as HTMLInputElement;
```

In both cases, using explicit type annotations and assertions can help improve the accuracy and usefulness of TypeScript's type system by providing more information about the intended types of your code.

